(4760, 'Pre-Council Exam 3', 'Pre-Council Exam 3 (uploaded past-paper set)', 'In the healthy lungs approximately 100ml of mucus is produced each day, mucus is produces from four main sources below except A. Tissue fluid transudate B. Sub mucosal gland C. Epithelial cells D. Goblet cells ANSWER C 12. The nurse is caring for a critically ill patient on mechanical ventilation. The physician identifies the need for a bronchoscopy, which requires informed consent. For the physician to obtain consent from the patient, the patient must be able to A. Be weaned from mechanical ventilation. B. Have knowledge and competence to make the decision. C. Nod his head that it is okay to proceed. D. Read and write in English. ANSWER B 13. The nurse is caring for a critically ill patient with terminal cancer. The monitor alarms and shows a potentially lethal rhythm. The patient has no pulse. The patient does not have a "do not resuscitate" order written on the chart. What is the appropriate nursing action? A. Contact the attending physician immediately to determine if CPR should be initiated. B. Contact the family immediately to determine if they want CPR to be started. C. Give emergency medications but withhold intubation. D. Initiate CPR and call a code. ANSWER D 14. When addressing an ethical dilemma, contextual, physiological, and personal factors of the situation must be considered. Which of the following is an example of a personal factor? A. The hospital has a policy that everyone must have an advance directive on the chart. B. The patient has lost 20 pounds in the past month and is fatigued all the time. C. The patient has told you what quality of life means and his or her wishes. D. The physician considers care to be futile in a given situation. ANSWER C 15. A specific request made by a competent person that directs medical care related to life-prolonging procedures in the event that person loses capacity to make decisions is called a A. "Do not resuscitate" order. B. Health care proxy. C. Informed consent. D. living will. ANSWER D 16. The nurse knows that which of the following statements about organ donation is true? A. Anyone who is comfortable approaching the family should discuss the option of organ donation. B. Brain death determination is required before organs can be retrieved for transplant. C. Donation of selected organs after cardiac death is ethically acceptable. D. Family members should consider the withdrawal of life support so that the patient can become an organ donor. ANSWER C 17. The nurse utilizes which of the following strategies when encountering an ethical dilemma in practice? (Select all that apply.) A. Change-of-shift report updates B. Ethics consultation services C. Pastoral care services D. Social work consultation ANSWER B 18. With which of these radiological examinations it is possible to detect blood flow velocity in arteries and veins? A. MRI B. CT angio C. US duplex D. Fluoroscopy ANSWER C 19. Which radiological examination plays leading role in the differential diagnosis of peripheral lung cancer and benign tumor/structure? A. X-rays B. CT C. MRI D. USS ANSWER B 20. What is the radiological symptom - free air accumulation in the pleural space? A. Pneumothorax B. Hydrothorax C. Pneumomediastinum D. Haemothorax ANSWER A 21. In ultrasonography stones in kidney or gallbladder causes: A. Acoustic shadow B. Acoustic enhancement C. Reverberation artefact D. Opacification ANSWER A 22. The best radiological examination for facial trauma is: A. X-ray B. CT C. MRI D. Doppler ANSWER B 23. What x-ray symptoms are characterized by bone fractures? A. Lucency line B. Defect of the bone contours C. Dislocation of bone parts D. All of the above ANSWER D 24. Which is the best radiological examination for fast and qualitative detection of muscle tendon rupture? A. X-ray B. US C. CT D. MRI ANSWER D 25. Which CT scan phases should be performed in a patient with suspected acute renal colic (kidney stone)? A. Native B. Native + portal venous C. Native + arterial D. All 4 dynamic phases ANSWER A 26. Female, 25th week of pregnancy, arrived at the emergency ward with complaints about pain in the right side, radiating to the back. Which radiological examination will you recommend in the emergency ward? A. Abdominal US B. Abdominal x-ray C. Abdominal CT D. MRI ANSWER A 27. Which of these is contraindication for X-ray examination? A. Metallic foreign body B. Adiposity C. Pregnancy D. No contraindications ANSWER C 28. A medical situation in which goals of care are not achievable is: A. Futility B. Incompetence C. Life prolonging procedure D. Persistent vegetative state ANSWER A 29. A patient who has profound neurological impairment with little or no chance of recovery is said to be: A. An organ donor B. Brain dead C. In a persistent vegetative state D. In a terminal condition ANSWER C 30. A critical care nurse connects a patient tube feeding through the cuff of ETT instead of the NG tube, this result in aspiration and hypoxemia. This situation is an example of: A. Assault. B. Battery. C. Futility D. Negligence. ANSWER D 31. All of the following are strategies for addressing ethical issues Except. A. Discussion during change of shift report B. Ethical consultation service C. Formal multidisplinary ethic committee D. Ethic referral services ANSWER A 32. Which one of the following is the primary imaging modality in ICU?', '["Ultrasonography", "Conventional X ray", "CT scan", "MRI"]'::jsonb, 1, NULL, 'Pre-Council', '🎓', true),
(4761, 'Pre-Council Exam 3', 'Pre-Council Exam 3 (uploaded past-paper set)', 'About the haemothorax choose the incorrect one', '["Accumulation of blood within the peritoneal space following blunt or penetrating trauma.", "Commonly associated with a pneumothorax and other extra thoracic injuries.", "Haemorrhage usually occurs from the lung parenchyma, and is often self-limiting, rather than from a specific vessel injury.", "Intercostal and internal mammary vessels are more commonly injured"]'::jsonb, 0, NULL, 'Pre-Council', '🎓', true),
